I feel like we're on same page but wanna check in - do you think we're asking client to choose between scenario 1 and 2 for us to "do" or are we suggessting they're relatdd and can both be addressed?
<@U4VTSDW7P> and <@U0XJFPSRL> /\ not trying to detract but i doo think we need to be concious of what we're asking for, vs what we're explaining in this deck

I think we're using both scenarios to show that different goals require a different kind of bot. The first scenario's goals could be solved with just a 1:1 bot OR a bot that's on the sidelines of a conversation. Scenario 2 feels more timely and wouldn't have the same effectiveness if the bot could only be built as a 1:1 bot. So yes, we are hoping they will choose between scenarios with an understanding of which kind of bot they will have to build to solve each.

<@U0XCJ372R> mentioned that in her research she has found no precedent for this "sideline" bot. Because of this, I think we are in the dark in terms of feasibility, privacy concerns, and mostly whether this interaction model would be annoying/invasive or well-received. If they choose this option, we could take the next week to sprint on it and map out detailed interaction flows, but I don't have a good grasp on what is within their development scope. Basically, a 1:1 bot seems more straightforward and has a set of "best practices" based on what others have tried.
